=80=94a
potential denouement to a heavily labored, highly publicized, and dysfuncti=
onal six-month public negotiation. Was there a last-minute wrinkle, I wonde=
red?

After my Zoom with Tara concluded, I rang Bill back and asked for the downl=
oad. Yes, he said with certainty, a funny thing had happened on the way to =
the Forum. Bill had just been working the phones and learned that the compl=
ex transaction between Redstone=E2=80=99s National Amusements Inc. and the =
combined forces of David Ellison=E2=80=99s Skydance and Gerry Cardinale=E2=
=80=99s RedBird was collapsing on the one-inch line. And the reasons for th=
e demise, Bill said, were utterly Shakespearean.

Some people around the deal believed that Charles Phillips, a former presid=
ent of Oracle and current Paramount director, had given Shari cold feet. Th=
ey wondered if Phillips was jonesing to take over Paramount, himself. (The =
company is currently run by an entirely untenable three-man interim =E2=80=
=9Coffice of
the C.E.O.=E2=80=9D structure.) Others were curious if he was exacting retr=
ibution on the Ellison clan over his departure from Oracle years earlier. E=
ither way, Bill reminded me, most deals die with age. And this latest twist=
 was going to kill this thing off, once and for all. That afternoon, the Jo=
urnal published a terse report acknowledging that Redstone was walking away=
 from the deal for noneconomic reasons. (Our inimitable partner Matt Bellon=
i broke the news of Phillips=E2=80=99s last-minute antagonism ( https://x.c=
om/MattBelloni/status/1800574223406223620?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%286%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%=
2F15%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3D=
f6c60617da42abd12a ).)

Bill, who has been chronicling the Redstone family=E2=80=99s dysfunction fo=
r years, was actually putting the finishing touches on an excellent story a=
bout David Solomon=E2=80=99s turnaround at Goldman Sachs. But we
eventually decided that that story would have to wait a couple days. (You=
=E2=80=99ll be able to read it in Dry Powder, Bill=E2=80=99s private email,=
 tomorrow. Sign up here ( https://puck.news/newsletters/dry-powder/?utm_cam=
paign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Bac=
kstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F15%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=
=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).) Instead, we reckoned that =
Bill should report out the devolution of the Paramount deal in all its gory=
 particulars.

Shari-Kiri ( https://puck.news/why-shari-redstone-killed-paramount-skydance=
-deal/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F14%2F24%29&utm_con=
tent=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F15%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_act=
ion&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), the resulting=
 story, is a masterpiece that details the economic challenges of the deal. =
Even with the $2.3 billion that Redstone would have received for NAI,
Paramount=E2=80=99s parentco, she would still have to pay off around $200 m=
illion in bank debt, plus the $175 million in preferred stock she owes BDT =
& MSD Partners, her financial advisor on the sale. The remaining $1.9 billi=
on would be divided between her and her late father Sumner Redstone=E2=80=
=99s five grandchildren, and subject to significant tax consequences. And t=
hen there would be a smorgasbord of shareholder lawsuits. =E2=80=9CIt was u=
gly,=E2=80=9D one longtime family observer told Bill. =E2=80=9CLike, scary =
ugly.=E2=80=9D

Bill=E2=80=99s piece also captures the underappreciated psychological eleme=
nts of the deal, like Redstone=E2=80=99s insecurity about her place in the =
mogul firmament, post-Paramount. Would she lose her booth at Dan Tana=E2=80=
=99s? Would she still be the belle of the ball at the Allen & Co media conf=
erence? Could she part with the heirloom that she had fought so hard to inh=
erit?

Meanwhile, Matt was also cooking up a second epic Redstone dispatch. Shari =
Redstone Hasn=E2=80=99t Solved Her Biggest Problem: Shari Redstone ( https:=
//puck.news/shari-redstone-hasnt-solved-her-biggest-problem-shari-redstone/=
?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=
=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F15%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) is a remarkable, i=
nsiderly tour de force that conveys that damage she wrought on Paramount du=
ring this extended sales process. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s kinda amazing that =
the public market values Paramount=E2=80=94which includes the long-term NFL=
 contract, all those movie and TV franchises, two growing streamers, and th=
e still-big cable TV cash flow=E2=80=94at merely $7.2 billion, not includin=
g that debt,=E2=80=9D Matt wrote. =E2=80=9CRemember, Paramount turned down =
$3 billion for Showtime, a brand it instead chose to murder, execution styl=
e, by starving it of content and folding it into Paramount+. Now the
whole company is worth
just two Showtimes and change. Remarkable.=E2=80=9D

If Puck=E2=80=99s industry-leading coverage of the Paramount debacle isn=E2=
=80=99t your thing, I=E2=80=99d turn your attention to Tara=E2=80=99s excel=
lent story. After we hopped off the Zoom, she set down to write a character=
istically cogent and witty piece, The Doug Bug ( https://puck.news/will-dou=
g-burgum-be-trumps-vice-president/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%286%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F15%2F=
24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c6061=
7da42abd12a ), chronicling the new Burgum-Trump bromance. In and around Mar=
-a-Lago, sources told Tara, Burgum has become known as =E2=80=9CDefault Dou=
g=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94an apparent knock that actually counts as high praise in=
 those quarters. =E2=80=9CDoug Burgum does no harm. Trump needs someone who=
 is sure-footed and would not contradict or upstage him, someone who unders=
tands he will not try to be the next future of the party,=E2=80=9D a
Trump advisor told Tara. =E2=80=9CI think he may get it by default. Everyon=
e else has a major flaw.=E2=80=9D

These stories of our time remain as unpredictable as ever. All that=E2=80=
=99s certain is that you should expect to read about them in Puck.

Have a great weekend,
Jon

